item.title: Inspectors
item.description:
last modified: December 02, 2024

Inspectors are figures of authority arriving at the end of the shift with one agenda or another.
The nature of the inspection is revealed at lunch. Yay.
They hail from various factions, reflected further in the challenges they present to the player.
Bureaucrat, abhors waste, is slow
Engineer, demands tight-tolerances regardless of application, is highly emotional
Politician, reactionary, will leverage representation for for their platform
Career General, demands the use of strong and exotic material, tends to break things
Cardinal, seeks to align production with faith, misrepresents symbolism
Artist, has no fucking idea what they want and no idea how to do it

item.title: Lunch
item.description:
last modified: December 02, 2024

Lunch occurs at the end of a shiftâ€™s fourth hour.
Lunch is provided to all employees at the facility.
Operators are permitted to converse with each other during lunch.
Players can talk to other operators during the collective meal, potentially gaining information and advancing the narrative.
In addition to the meal provided, the player can explore the break room and fridge for additional food and drink to fuel the remainder of their shift, buffing certain aspects.

item.title: O'Neill Cylinder
item.description:
last modified: December 02, 2024
An O'Neill cylinder is a concept for a massive space habitat proposed by physicist Gerard K. O'Neill in the 1970s. It consists of two counter-rotating cylinders, each several kilometers long and a few kilometers in diameter, that rotate around their longitudinal axis to create artificial gravity through centrifugal force. The interior of the cylinder is designed to support a self-sustaining human population with Earth-like living conditions.
https://www.projectrho.com/public_html/rocket/spacecolony.php

item.title: Operator Design Document
item.description:
last modified: December 02, 2024


self-management and optimization
tension between flow and alienation of work
collective organizing and "social" machines
Operator is a science-fiction narrative videogame using rogue-like game mechanics of accumulation and ascension against loss and repetition. Working as a CNC machine operator, the player character fabricates widgets in a manufacturing facility as they grapple with hierarchies of labor and power. The game reveals its strange world encompassing this facility--an ostensibly hermetic and self-sustaining space station (See O'Neill Cylinder)--to the player through investigating the material products of their work and workspace in addition to conversing with their coworkers, bosses, and interpreting their glitchy CNC machine.
In rogue-like fashion, the player is tasked with learning to optimize and manage their efforts and resources as they compete with their coworkers to bid on the most prestigious jobs. Through the promise of greater rewards and power within this repetitive cycle, this aspect of game encourages flow and focus on individual achievement.
However, through downtime mechanics, the player is invited to explore their environment and socialize with their coworkers, revealing more about the condition of their world from a perspective other than the manager's bulletins. These interactions aim to entangle the player and their character into a network of other actors. The player is charged with making additional decisions in their future work as they consider new relationships, dependencies and possibilities.

Operator utilizes a limited first person perspective, allowing the player to move along and inspect different, curated points of interest using standard arrow keys or directional pad controls. Through pointing, clicking and dragging a cursor within these points of interest enables object interaction and exploration that drives the gameâ€™s loop and narrative progression.
A playthrough begins at the start of a shift. Each carries continuity from the previous while introducing progression and randomization across various aspects. The player selects a part order to manufacture from those available on the job board. Now charged with fulfilling a part's requirements to specification the player enters an encounter.
The player must attend to the demanded accuracy, delivery time, and quantity of the part order as they develop a procedure for a production-run of the part using the cutting tools and programs available to them with help from their CNC machine. These demands requires the player to balance the accuracy, delivery time, and quantity of their task against the ever dulling and diminishing tool-life of their cutting tools in their inventory.
Completed part orders are graded based on how well they meet their respective requirements. Successful fulfilment of part orders rewards the player with resources. Exceeding requirements does not reward additional resources, but may be leveraged strategically within a shift. A limited number of passes within a shift are allowed for failing to deliver a part order to specification. Exceeding this allowance, player characters are fired/composted resulting in permanent death of this character and loss of all accumulation and progress. A composted operatorâ€™s resources are distributed among workers at the facility. Surviving a shift allows for the player to move on with their accumulated resources. and chits to the next dayâ€™s shift.
If a player survives to the end of a shift with a certain level of production-runs accomplished, they are faced with a challenging, overtime part order akin to a boss encounter. Succeeding these encounters grant a meeting with an elite customer offer additional choices that offer material incentives and narrative impact.

Operatorâ€™s visuals subvert the photorealistic tendencies of the Unreal Engine 5â€™s cutting edge real-time lighting techniques such as Lumen, however a low resolution aesthetic is chosen to highlight features and actions in the world while conjuring an otherworldly mood. Emphasizing the electronic interfaces and materiality of the tools and machines in the facility, UI elements are strictly displayed dietetically.

Over the generations living and dying--working--as different operators, players will witness the overturning of regimes through changes in the material world that their facility both supports and depends on.
The player operates their CNC machine to produce components that are often markedly in service to different clients of interest groups vying for power. Through 1) completing shift work with their CNC machine tool, 2) failing to fill orders, and 3) exploring their workspace, players gain insight into the state of the world surrounding the facility. Players must balance their use of tools and time to 1) fill component fabrication orders or 2) work between jobs to cooperate with coworkers and future operators or 3) divert resources to insurgents in order to survive or facilitate revolutions.

item.title: randomization
item.description:
last modified: December 02, 2024
Different world conditions are present in a given shift, adding additional challenges and opportunities for players.
The job board displays the availability and requirements of of the part orders in need of fabrication.
From this board, players can view component drawings to decide which components to take on during a shift. Other operators are working in the facility: there will always be an initial surplus of components to choose from, diminishing as the shift proceeds.
Hints at upcoming events within a shift are also visible alongside the job board to help players strategize which components to choose from. Except for lunch, and inspection, each shift these events are randomized and include traveling salespeople, and garbage collectors.

item.title: rogue-like
item.description:
last modified: December 02, 2024
A genre of video game characterized by procedurally generated levels, permanent death of the player character, and a focus on replayability. Each playthrough provides a familiar yet varied experience, with slight changes in design and challenge encouraging adaptability. Progression typically involves increasing difficulty, rewarding players for mastering mechanics and strategies over time. Roguelikes often emphasize resource management, exploration, and decision-making within a framework of high-stakes gameplay.
